          <li><a href="#quick-verdict">Quick Verdict</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily sit-to-stand use with a dual-monitor arm</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Autonomous SmartDesk 2</strong> is the best $299 motorized standing desk you can buy, and it shows. The single motor moves the desktop at a respectable 1.3 inches per second, the memory keypad saves four height presets, and the 60 by 30 inch surface holds a full setup. It wobbles noticeably at full height with a heavy monitor arm, the plastic feet feel cheap, and customer service is slow — but if your budget caps at $350, it is the desk to buy.
      </div>

      <p>Autonomous built its business on selling a motorized standing desk for under $300 when competitors charged $500 to $700. The SmartDesk 2 is the second generation of that strategy: a single-motor frame, a steel leg set, a laminated MDF desktop, and a four-preset memory keypad, all for $299. We bought one at retail, assembled it in 90 minutes, and used it daily for 60 days with a dual-monitor arm, a mechanical keyboard, and a tower PC on the desktop to see how it holds up under real load.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against other standing desks, see our <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-under-300/">best standing desk under $300</a> roundup. If your budget stretches higher, our <a href="/reviews/uplift-v2-review/">Uplift V2 review</a> and <a href="/reviews/flexispot-e7-review/">FlexiSpot E7 review</a> cover the more stable dual-motor alternatives — but the SmartDesk 2 is the right pick if price is the deciding factor.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Motor Speed and Lift Performance</h3>
      <p>The SmartDesk 2 uses a single motor mounted in the crossbar under the desktop. It moves the desk at about 1.3 inches per second under load, which is faster than most desks under $350 and comparable to the FlexiSpot E7's 1.2 inches per second. A full transition from seated (29 inches) to standing (47 inches) takes about 14 seconds — long enough that you notice it, short enough that you do not dread it.</p>

      <p>The lift capacity is rated at 270 pounds. We loaded the desk with a 34-inch ultrawide monitor on a gas-arm mount (18 lb), a tower PC (24 lb), a mechanical keyboard and mouse (4 lb), and assorted books and gear (about 15 lb) — roughly 61 pounds total. The motor handled it without straining, and the speed barely changed. The single-motor design is louder than the dual-motor desks in the same tier: we measured 52 dB at full extension, compared to 44 dB on the FlexiSpot E7. It is not loud enough to interrupt a call, but it is noticeable.</p>

      <p>The motor has a soft start and soft stop, which prevents the jerky lurch that cheaper desks suffer from. The transition is smooth and predictable, and the desk does not overshoot your preset height. For a $299 single-motor desk, the motion quality is genuinely good.</p>

      <h3>Stability: The SmartDesk 2's Real Weakness</h3>
      <p>Stability is where the SmartDesk 2's budget engineering shows. At seated height (under 38 inches), the desk is solid. Type firmly, lean on it, rest your elbows — there is no perceptible wobble. The steel legs and the crossbar do their job, and the desk feels as stable as anything twice the price.</p>

      <p>The problem appears at full standing height. Above 44 inches, the steel legs flex and the desk develops a noticeable side-to-side sway. We measured about 4 millimeters of movement at the desktop edge with a heavy monitor arm at 47 inches — enough that you can see the monitors wobble when you type firmly. The FlexiSpot E7 and Uplift V2 show under 1 millimeter under the same load, because they use thicker legs and dual motors that keep the desktop level.</p>

      <p>If you sit most of the day and stand occasionally, the wobble is tolerable. If you spend hours at a time at full standing height with a heavy monitor arm, it becomes genuinely annoying. The workaround is to keep your monitor arm centered (off-center weight amplifies the sway) and to avoid leaning on the desk while standing. But if stability matters to you, spend the extra $100 to $200 on a dual-motor desk.</p>

      <h3>Desktop: Materials and Surface</h3>
      <p>Autonomous offers the SmartDesk 2 in several top materials: a laminated MDF in black, white, or walnut; a bamboo top; and an oak option. We tested the bamboo top, which is the most popular and the one Autonomous markets hardest. The bamboo is solid (not a veneer), pre-finished with a matte sealant that resists scratches and water rings, and feels premium for the price.</p>

      <p>The 60 by 30 inch desktop is generous. It holds a 34-inch ultrawide monitor, a laptop, a keyboard, a mouse, a lamp, and a coffee mug with room to spare. The 30-inch depth is enough for a monitor arm to sit behind the display without crowding the keyboard. Edges are gently rounded, which is more comfortable on the forearms than a sharp 90-degree edge.</p>

      <p>The one weakness of the bamboo top is that it dents if you drop something heavy on it. We dropped a metal water bottle from 18 inches and it left a 2-millimeter dent. The laminated MDF options are more dent-resistant but feel less premium. Pick bamboo for feel; pick MDF for durability.</p>

      <h3>Keypad and Memory Presets</h3>
      <p>The SmartDesk 2 ships with a digital keypad that stores four height presets. You press and hold a numbered button (1 through 4) to save the current height, and tap it to return to that height. The keypad also has up and down arrows for manual adjustment and a small LED display showing the current height in inches.</p>

      <p>The presets work reliably across our 60-day test. We saved a seated height and a standing height to buttons 1 and 2 and used them daily without issue. The keypad remembers the height even after a power loss, which is important if you unplug the desk or have a breaker trip.</p>

      <p>The keypad's weaknesses are cosmetic. The buttons feel mushy and have a vague travel — they do not click with the satisfying snap of the Uplift V2's keypad. The LED display is dim and hard to read in a bright room, and it only shows height, not weight or preset names. These are minor annoyances, but they are the kind of details that separate a $299 desk from a $599 desk.</p>

      <h3>Assembly: Plan for 90 Minutes and a Second Person</h3>
      <p>Assembly is the SmartDesk 2's hidden cost. Plan for 90 minutes from unboxing to a finished desk, and you need a second person for one step: lifting the 40 to 55 pound desktop onto the assembled frame and aligning it with the mounting bolts. Autonomous ships the desk in two boxes (frame and desktop), and the packaging is sturdy enough that our unit arrived without damage.</p>

      <p>The frame bolts together with four leg bolts, two crossbar bolts, and the motor cable — about 30 minutes with the included Allen key and wrench. The desktop attaches with eight screws from underneath, which is where the second person earns their keep: one person holds the desktop steady while the other drives the screws. A cordless drill with a hex bit cuts about 15 minutes off the build, but be careful not to over-torque and strip the MDF.</p>

      <p>The keypad and motor wiring are pre-installed inside the legs — you just plug the keypad cable into the control box and route it along the crossbar with the included zip ties. Autonomous includes a cable tray under the desktop, which is a nice touch at this price and keeps your power strip and cables off the floor.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and the Plastic Feet Problem</h3>
      <p>The SmartDesk 2's frame is steel, the legs are steel, and the crossbar is steel — all good. The feet, however, are plastic. The four leveling feet that sit under the legs are a hard plastic with a thin rubber pad, and they feel cheap. They do their job on a flat floor, but on a slightly uneven floor they creak under load, and if you drag the desk sideways to reposition it, the plastic feet can crack.</p>

      <p>We cracked one foot within the first week while sliding the desk 6 inches to the left to reach a power outlet. Autonomous sent a replacement, but it took a week to arrive and the customer service interaction (see below) was not smooth. If you need to reposition the desk, lift it — do not drag it. Replacement feet are $12 from Autonomous, or you can buy aftermarket rubber feet from a hardware store for $5.</p>

      <p>The rest of the build quality is solid for the price. The leg glides are smooth, the motor mount is rigid, and the desktop sits level on the frame without shimming. The cable tray is metal, not plastic. The keypad mount is sturdy. Autonomous cut costs where they could (the feet, the keypad feel) without compromising the load-bearing structure.</p>

      <h3>Customer Service: Slow but Eventually Helpful</h3>
      <p>Autonomous customer service is the SmartDesk 2's weakest point that has nothing to do with the desk itself. We tested the support process by emailing about the cracked foot and a missing bolt. Email replies took 3 to 5 business days each, and the first reply was a canned response asking for photos and a video of the issue. The phone line had a 25-minute hold time, and the representative was helpful once connected but could not expedite the replacement.</p>

      <p>The replacement foot arrived 8 days after the original request, which meant the desk sat unused for a week because we did not want to put weight on three feet. The missing bolt was never sent; we bought a replacement at a hardware store for $0.40. If you have a problem during assembly, expect a delay.</p>

      <p>The 5-year frame warranty is genuine, and Autonomous does honor it — but you need patience. If you are the kind of buyer who wants responsive support, the Uplift V2 and FlexiSpot E7 both answer emails within one business day and ship replacements in 2 to 3 days. You are paying for that service in the higher price.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested the SmartDesk 2 against the FlexiSpot E7 and the Uplift V2, the two desks it competes with most directly. Here is how they stack up:</p>

