          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>FlexiSpot E7</strong> costs $100 more and solves the SmartDesk 2's two biggest problems: it has dual motors (no wobble at full height) and a taller max height (50 inches, friendly to users over 6 foot 2). If your budget stretches to $399, the E7 is the better desk. See our <a href="/reviews/flexispot-e7-review/">FlexiSpot E7 review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Uplift V2</strong> at $599 is the premium benchmark. It is faster, more stable, has a better keypad, more desktop options, and the best customer service in the category. If you spend 8 hours a day at your desk and can afford it, the V2 is worth the premium. But it is twice the price of the SmartDesk 2, and for many buyers that gap is not worth closing.</p>

      <p>If you cannot justify a motorized desk at all, a <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-converter/">standing desk converter</a> sits on top of your existing desk for $150 to $250 and requires zero assembly. It is the right pick if you rent or move often.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the SmartDesk 2 if your budget caps at $350 and you want a motorized standing desk with memory presets. For $299 you get a desk that works, holds a full setup, and moves between seated and standing heights reliably. The wobble at full height is real but tolerable if you sit more than you stand.</p>

      <p>Get the bamboo top. It is the same price as the laminated MDF options and feels meaningfully more premium. The bamboo is solid (not veneer), resists scratches, and develops a patina over time that hides wear. Avoid the oak option unless you specifically want the lighter color — it costs $30 more and dents more easily.</p>

      <p>Buy a $12 set of rubber replacement feet at the same time. The stock plastic feet are the SmartDesk 2's most likely failure point, and replacing them upfront avoids the week-long wait for an Autonomous replacement if one cracks. Rubber feet also grip hard floors better and reduce the desk's tendency to slide.</p>

      <p>Skip the SmartDesk 2 if you are tall (over 6 foot 2), if you run a heavy multi-monitor arm at full standing height, or if you need responsive customer service. The FlexiSpot E7 ($399) and Uplift V2 ($599) both reach 50 inches and are rock-solid at full height. The extra $100 to $300 buys stability and support that the SmartDesk 2 cannot match.</p>

      <p>Pair the SmartDesk 2 with a good <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-under-500/">ergonomic chair</a> — the desk handles your standing posture, but you still need a chair that handles your sitting posture for the hours you are seated.</p>

